column10: This design aims to interpret a traditional Chinese "scholar's rock" by sculpting, molding, and fabricating a sculpture that captures the magnificence experienced when viewing these rocks. The scholar's rock sculpture is positioned at the center of a serene rock garden, surrounded by hand-carved log benches for viewing and contemplation.

column10: This project features a “Sankofa” bird made from mixed-media and recycled materials. In Africa, a bird looking backwards over its tail represents the Sankofa symbol, which means “go back and fetch it.” It is an understanding that our past(s) holds important information to move us forward in life. There is a mosaic on the exterior of the bird and mural on the interior representing Bronzeville history. QR codes are integrated into the mural design to allow visitors with smartphones, to access sites with information about the images included in the mural, as well as, information on Bronzeville, the Chicago Park District and the Field Museum.

column10: This circular sculpture, or "ronda," consists of interlocking butterfly forms and is inspired by the magic symbolism of the monarch butterfly, harmony with nature, and migration. The center of the space features native plants and repurposed cement blocks as rustic seating.

column10: The art installation called Caracol, which means "snail" and "shell" in Spanish, represents the immigrant's longing to belong while preserving their memories and identity. Just as snails play a crucial role in the natural world by breaking down plant matter and enriching the soil, immigrants also contribute to and revitalize the society they join. The spiral structure of Caracol symbolizes the continual movement from the familiar to the unknown, and the installation includes a versatile table, murals with language and imagery, a stage, and a Mesoamerican numbers hopscotch game.

column10: The new space in Bronzeville was created by community members in partnership with the Chicago Park District. It features modern, geometric seating and reflective elements in a shaded woodland near Oakwood Blvd. The design was inspired by the woven willow sculptural forms and mission of Sounding Bronzeville, the previous Gathering Space. Bronzewood showcases sturdy oak sculptures that pay tribute to the resilience and strength of African-Americans who migrated north and now reside in the Bronzeville community, similar to Sounding Bronzeville.
